517
Bounties Paid to New Recruits.
\tTo increase the number of men voluntarily offering their services, new recruits are offered higher bounties, averaging 600 dollars per man. The payment is hoped to be a strong incentive in making military service a more attractive option. \n\tSo far, the bounties have increased the number of volunteers, but there are also reports of a higher than usual rate of desertion among the new recruits, dubbed "bounty-men" by the veterans. The veterans are disgruntled as they are serving without such compensation and the new recruits often avoid danger, disobeying orders and fleeing to the rear as soon as they get the chance.\n\tTo prevent bounty jumping, only part of the bounty is paid up front and the rest is paid after the service period ends. But still, the number of men deserting has increased and reports tell of these deserters joining up in other units in different states to collect new bounties. The recruiting officials have no way of preventing such behavior.
