The Union Passes Militia Act IV.
\tThe Union has passed a militia act, increasing the service of new volunteers to 36 months or the war's end. This will keep veterans with the armies for a longer time than before. Lately, Congress has also sanctioned further recruitment, first to a total number of 500,000, but this upper limit seems to be flexible if required so by the President.\n\tHaving the men serve for a longer period of time is hoped to increase the effectiveness of Union armies. Three years should be a long enough period to see the end of the war and for this reason the contract will expire in the case where the Union is victorious earlier.\n\tAt the same time, citizens are not as keen as before, considering they would be offering their services for such a long period. Recruiters are reporting less volunteers willing to serve and less veterans willing to renew their contracts. Immigrants are an exception as many are out of work, and there is an increasing number of German and Irish immigrants joining up to serve.
