1
U.S. Regulars Fighting like Devils.
\tBy the mid 19th Century, the size of the U.S. Army remained low, at well under 20,000 troops in total. The size of the army had been sufficient for peace time duties, consisting mainly of manning the coastal fortifications and guarding the vast frontier against Indian raids. While the army has not seen large scale warfare, most of the regulars have at least some combat experience from fighting Indians.\n\tWith the secession crisis at hand, the plan was to distribute the regular army units among the provisional army militia units, to strengthen their resolve by setting an example and to help in training. The Regular Act orders differently. Instead, the regulars are formed into brigades, and the recruitment of more regulars has commenced to reinforce the brigades into full strength units.\n\tWhile this order creates a small number of well-trained units, this decision also creates two competing sub-armies, the regulars and the volunteers. The latter are expected to suffer from this arrangement and the military experience of the army as a whole takes a hit.
