The Confederacy Passes Bank Act!
Establishment of National Banks made Possible!
Credit Rating Improved!
Uproar in the States, as Green-backs Lose Status!
Government Treasury Increased!
518
The Confederacy Passes Bank Act.
\tThe C.S. government has passed a National Banking Act which imposes a system of free banking at a national level. What this means, is that a portion of a national banks' capital has to be made up of government bonds. The government can now establish new national banks, increasing available capital in the region, allowing cheaper loans and so encouraging businesses to expand.\n\tThe act has improved the C.S. credit rating, which means that additional cheaper loans are available. As banks are required to buy bonds, the government treasury is increased considerably.\n\tThe Act has been received with anger by the States, as greenbacks are losing status. The states' officials and bankers think that the government is reducing states rights in order to govern federally.
